   ABSTRACT   
   &nbsp;   
   &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;    The rapid growth of online communication platforms has led to a significant increase in job-related fraud, particularly through channels such as email and messaging applications. This paper presents  FraudShield , an intelligent system designed to identify and classify fraudulent job messages using machine learning and natural language processing techniques. The proposed approach processes textual content through preprocessing steps and transforms it into numerical representations using feature extraction methods such as TF-IDF. Multiple classification algorithms, including Logistic Regression, Support Vector Machines, and Random Forest, are implemented and evaluated to determine the most effective model.  
  In addition to classification, the system incorporates an explainability mechanism that highlights suspicious patterns and keywords contributing to the prediction, thereby improving user trust and transparency. The model is trained on curated datasets and enhanced with user-reported scam messages, enabling continuous learning and adaptation to emerging fraud patterns. Experimental evaluation demonstrates that the system achieves high accuracy in distinguishing fraudulent and legitimate job messages. The proposed solution provides a practical and scalable approach for real-time scam detection and contributes to improving digital safety in recruitment-related communications.  
   &nbsp;   
   Key words:        Explainable Artificial Intelligence, Job Scam Detection, Machine Learning, Phishing, Text Classification

